ks, from revenge plays to Shakespeare’s first history tetralogy and beyond, Mullaney explores how post-Reformation drama not only exposed these faultlines of society on stage but also provoked playgoers in the audience to acknowledge their shared differences. He demonstrates that our most lasting works of culture remain powerful largely because of their deep roots in the emotional landscape of their times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEmotions in literature. 0aEnglish dramaxHistory and criticismxEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  afaith, identity, emotion, affect, belief, reformation, religion, spirituality, elizabethan england, drama, shakespeare, habermas, hamlet, stage, publication, theater, history, memory, forgetting, irony, feeling, merchant of venice, titus andronicus, spanish tragedy, nonfiction, literature, playwright, theatrical space, performance studies, early modern, subjectivity, dramatic interpretation, technology, amphitheatre, community.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226117096423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226117096/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles